<subSubSection pageId="83" pageNumber="362" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="83.[175,1383,2812,3473]" pageId="83" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[176,441,2894,2923]" pageId="83" pageNumber="362">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body ¢.172-173 mm, tail 166-182 mm, hindfoot 33-35-5 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Painted Woodrat is medium-sized, with orange-rufous to ferruginous color along cheeks, shoulders, and sides. Head region and back are darkened by black-tipped hairs. Venter is nearly white to salmon, with plumbeous basal color. Tail is long and slender and covered with short hairs, indistinctly bicolored (dusky above and paler below). Ears are relatively small with short, dusky hairs. Forefeet are yellowish white, hindfeet are dusky or pale fulvous, and toes are white. Skull is less robust; zygomatic arch less arched at anterior.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="83" pageNumber="362" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="83.[175,1383,2812,3473]" pageId="83" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[176,287,3244,3277]" pageId="83" pageNumber="362">Habitat.</emphasis>
Generally, montane woodlands and shrubby vegetation up to elevations of 3048 m. The Painted Woodrat is typically found along rocky outcroppings associated with cloud forest habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
